<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
This species is characterised by its decumbent habit, coarsely hispid indumentum and long, caudate sepals. It is similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pseudocalystegia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea pseudocalystegia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but the leaves are simple, the sepals and bracteoles are shorter and the pedicels much longer. It also somewhat resembles 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="langsdorffii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea langsdorffii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but the flowers are often solitary and never in many-flowered cymes, and the leaves are not whitish beneath.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
